Exploring Red Wine Quality by Jin Lim

The Red Wine dataset concerns the red variant of the Portuguese Vinho Verde wine. It contains 1599 observations and 11 input variables, as well as an output variable called quality on a scale of 0 (very bad)-10 (very excellent). Our task is to determine which variables have statistically significant impacts on the quality of wine.

This dataset is provided by Udacity and is named wineQualityReds.csv

Univariate Plots Section

Lets look at quality first. From the plot, it appears that most wines are of average (5-6) quality. This is consistent with my expectations as most wine-tasters will usually not grade in extremes as a part of human nature. That is, they will average the results in their head and save extreme scores for extreme wines.

For acidity, Fixed Acidity seems to be fairly normally-distributed, with a positive or right skew. Volatile Acidity seems to be bimodal, with peaks at 0.4 and 0.6.

We scale Citric Acid by log10 due to its long right-tail. Interestingly, the transformation now yields a long left-tail. This could be further explored in the bivariate analysis section.

Residual sugar is very positively skewed and has peaks around 2. It has a lot of outliers on the right-tail.

Chlorides has a similar distribution to Residual Sugar. We see a strong concentration of points around the median and extreme outliers.

Relative to the other plots, Free Sulfur Dioxide has a relatively dispersed distribution, but again it has extreme outliers on its right-tail. Total Sulfur Dioxide is less-dispersed, but still follows the same pattern.

Both Density and pH are very normally distributed, with concentrations around 0.995-1 and 3.2-3.5 respectively.

At first glance, Sulphates is certainly more positively skewed than Density and PH, but I would say the data is still fairly normally-distributed around 0.6. It does not have as many extreme outliers as Chlorides and Free/Total Sulphur Dioxide.

Alcohol is right-skewed, though not to the extent of Chlorides and Free/Total Sulphur Dioxide.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 1599 observations of red wine with twelve features and a (removed) unique identifier. All values are numerical save for quality, which is an integer.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main feature of interest is the output variable quality.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

I would expect alcohol and residual sugar to be fairly positively-correlated with quality. On the other hand, the more extreme the value of pH, the less quality should result.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

No, I did not. I could have perhaps combined fixed/volatile acidity into something like total acidity, but I do not think that would affect the quality very much by itself.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

  1. Citric Acid has a large number of 0 values. I wonder how it can be that some wines do not have this value if most are made of similar grapes. Also, scaling Citric Acid by log10 reverses the tail.
  2. I was also surprised by the number of extreme outliers in many of the variables. If most of the wines have an average rating, this could mean that for some features, going in an extreme direction does not actually have a signficant impact on taste, if at all.
  3. For several plots, I did my best to limit the most extreme outliers via scaling limits.

Bivariate Plots Section

The top 4 factors correlated with wine quality (>0.2) are: alcohol (0.476), volatile acidity (-0.391), sulphates (0.251), and finally citric acid (0.226).

We converted quality from an integer to a factor in order to plot with box plots. At least one of our assumptions was right: the higher the alcohol content of the wine, the higher the wine is rated.

My assumption about residual sugar was wrong. This is the sugar left after fermentation, so perhaps wine-tasters put more stock by other flavors than sweetness.

The more volatile acids there are in a wine, the lower it is rated. Our assumption was based on pH, in that extreme values will have lower scores. Let us examine that next.

And oddly enough, it would appear that lesser pH (more acidity) has a correlation with higher quality. So now we have an interesting relationship on our hands: volatile acidity is negatively correlated with quality, but recall citric acid is positively correlated (0.226). It would be worth examining all the acidic factors on a log scale against pH to understand how each factor works in determining acidity.

Fixed and Citric acids correlate with pH as we expected; that is to say, the more acids, the lower the pH value.

Volatile acidity is odd. The overview suggests it is acetic acid, and that high concentrations impart a vinegar taste. It is, however, positively correlated with pH, and yet we know lower pH means more acidity. This should mean more volatile acidity -> lower pH. Perhaps the more acid is present as volatile instead of fixed, the more it evaporates, thus leaving a less acidic pH (assuming wine-tasters wait before drinking).

And here we have the sulphates and sulphateslog10 plots. The more sulphates are present in a wine, the higher its quality. This is consistent as sulphates act as antimicrobials and antioxidants, and thus help preserve a wine. We also decided to scale the plot due to the factors original right skew.

Finally, citric acid and quality. Recall we reversed the skew of citric acid when we plotted it in log10. Here are both graphs, and it can be seen that higher citric acid values result in a higher quality. There are outliers where crossing a certain threshold results in drastically lowered quality, but the general rule still stands.

And just to be thorough, here are the plots for two other factors that had correlations close to 0.2: density (-0.175) and total sulfur dioxide (-0.185).

Density can be explained, I think. Alcohol is lighter than water, and we already know alcohol was one of our strongest correlative variables; thus, the more alcohol, the less density and the higher the quality. It could also contribute to an airy feeling. Well test that in the next plot.

Total sulfur dioxide is also consistent in that more of it can affect the taste of the wine, though the box plot suggests this is an inconsistent correlation at best.

Here we see that more alcohol results in less density, so density is more a function of that than a predictor of quality.

I did not expect one factor to be able to fully explain quality when there are so many other variables at play. Alcohol will be an important piece of the puzzle.

Multivariate Plots Section

As can be seen from the plot, higher quality wines in blue colors tend to have high alcohol content and low densities. Holding alcohol constant, density has no real explanatory effect on wine quality, confirming our prior guess that it was alcohol contributing to lower density and its slight positive correlation with quality.

The highest quality wines tend to have low volatile acidity and high alcohol content.

For sulphates, generally higher quality wines tend to have higher levels of alcohol and sulphates. Lets put these three variables which had the highest correlation with quality (alcohol, volatile acidity, sulphates) together.

Weve changed the color coding for this plot. Now, the log10 of sulphates ranges from red (low sulphates) to blue (high sulphates), and the graph is faceted over quality with volatile acidity on the y-axis and alcohol on the x-axis. As a general rule, higher-quality wines have more alcohol (concentrated right), less volatile acidity (concentrated low), and more sulphates (more blue than red).

We scaled sulphates by log10 in order to normalize its right tail.

Finally, we look at citric acid using the same format. This one is not as clear as when alcohol was the x-axis, but again, you can see a general pattern where higher quality wines have more sulphates, less volatile acidity and slightly more right-skew.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

Our strongest relationship and the best predictor of wine rating. The higher the alcohol content of a wine, the better the tasters rated it. Looking at the plot, means and medians tend to coincide for each facet of quality, and thus for a particular quality grade, the distribution is fairly normal.

Plot Two

Description Two

And the next three strongest predictors. Volatile acidity (acetic acid) has a consistent downward effect on wine rating. Sulphates (antimicrobial and antioxidant additives) have a consistent upward effect on wine rating. Citric acid (affects freshness of wine) has a small but noticeably positive effect on rating. These three work with alcohol to produce the best-rated wines.

Plot Three

Description Three

And so, putting all four factors (Alcohol, Volatile Acidity, Sulphates and Citric Acid together) together. The best-rated wines tend to have a high alcohol content and low volatile acidity. They also tend to have more citric acid and sulphates.

Reflection

The Red Wine dataset concerns the red variant of the Portuguese Vinho Verde wine. It contains 1599 observations and 11 input variables, as well as an output variable called quality on a scale of 0 (very bad)-10 (very excellent). There is no single fully-robust explanatory relationship between these variables and quality; rather, the inputs all work together to guide wine rating. The four variables with the most driving force are alcohol (0.476), volatile acidity (-0.391), sulphates (0.251) and citric acid (0.226). These variables were the main point of focus in most of this projects visualizations.

Observations and reflections on variables:
1. Alcohol: Alcohol is the most correlated factor with wine quality. The higher the alcohol rating, the better the tasters rated the wine. Perhaps the alcohol content itself imparts a sharper and stronger taste. More likely, alcohol content is a result of fermentation length; the longer the fermentation, the more alcohol extracted, and the greater the perception of quality and perhaps subtle tastes imparted by aging.
2. Volatile Acidity: Or acetic acid. The more acetic acid, the lower the wine is rated. Obviously, a vinegar-like taste cannot be good for ratings.
3. Sulphates: These are added to wines in order to combat bacterial growth and prevent spoilage. It would make sense that wines with the least spoilage taste the best.
4. Citric Acid: Another additive to wines. The large number of 0 citric acid entries in this dataframe suggests that it is also a personal decision by the winemaker himself. Adding this can impart a fresh feel to the wines taste, though again, this is at the winemakers discretion; not all good wines require that zing.

I was very surprised that residual sugar had almost zero correlation with wine rating. Perhaps that is the point: I am not a wine-drinker, and I tend to enjoy sweeter drinks. Obviously, ones palate must be broadened in order to truly appreciate the subtleties of such a high-class beverage.

Wine-tasting is a complex subject, and is itself subject to human biases. In that vein, perhaps it would have served the data well to include qualitative or categorical variables to the list, instead of purely numerical ones. Things like the color and hue of the wine might have contributed to rating as well. At the end of the day, the linear model I constructed was too simple to adequately explain wine rating. Wine is no doubt more than the sum of its parts, and certainly more than a few chemical components.
